revision.text:
[[Image:Hollywood gpu.png|thumb|right|150px|ATI "Hollywood" GPU within the Wii console]]

'''Hollywood''' is the name of the [[graphics processing unit]] (GPU) used in [[Nintendo|Nintendo's]] [[Wii]] [[video game console]]. It was designed by [[Advanced Micro Devices|AMD's]] graphics product division, [[ATI Technologies|ATI]], and is manufactured using the same [[90 nm]] CMOS process<ref name="hard_japan">{{ja icon}}{{cite web| url=http://www.nintendo.co.jp/n10/e3_2006/wii/index.html| title=Wiiの概要 (Wii本体)| publisher=Nintendo |accessdate=2007-01-03}}</ref> as the [[Broadway (microprocessor)|"Broadway"]] processor. Very few official details were released to the public by Nintendo, ATI, or [[IBM]]. The Hollywood GPU is reportedly based on the Nintendo GameCube's "Flipper" GPU and is clocked 50% higher at 243&nbsp;MHz,<ref name="IGNTech">{{cite web|title=IGN: Revolution's Horsepower|date=2006-03-29|publisher=IGN|accessdate=2006-12-23|url= http://wii.ign.com/articles/699/699118p1.html}}</ref> though none of the [[clock rate]]s have been confirmed by Nintendo, IBM, or ATI.

GPU is fixed function only.

The Hollywood is a [[multi-chip module]] (MCM) package containing two [[Die (integrated circuit)|die]]s under the cover. One of the two chips, codenamed ''Napa'', controls the I/O functions, [[Random-access memory|RAM]] access, and the actual GPU with its embedded [[Dynamic random-access memory|DRAM]], and measures 8 × 9&nbsp;mm. The other, codenamed ''Vegas'', holds the Audio [[Digital signal processor|DSP]] and the 24 MB of "internal" [[1T-SRAM]] and measures 13.5 × 7&nbsp;mm.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}

The Hollywood also contains an [[ARM architecture|ARM926]] core, which has been unofficially nicknamed the ''Starlet''.<ref name="Wiibrew">{{cite web|title=Starlet|url=http://wiibrew.org/wiki/Starlet|work=Wiibrew|accessdate=2008-02-20}}</ref> This embedded microprocessor performs many of the I/O functions, including controlling the wireless functionality, [[Universal Serial Bus|USB]], the optical disc drive, and other miscellaneous functions. It also acts as the security controller of the system, performing encryption and authentication functions. The Hollywood includes hardware implementations of [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]] and [[SHA-1]], to speed up these functions. Communication with the main CPU is accomplished via an [[Inter-process communication|IPC]] mechanism. The Starlet performs the [[WiiConnect24]] functions while the Wii console is in standby mode.<ref name="Wiibrew"/>


